1.0 	INTRODUCTION
Fairview 97 is located within the producing coal seam gas field, Fairview, in the
Bowen Basin. The nearest town is Injune which is approximately 50 km away.
The well is located 1.45km south-east of Fairview 52 and 1.8km east of Fairview-
34. The location lies east of the Comet Ridge platform crest. The well is spaced
along the east-west 2 kilometre grid of the current field development plan. Its
location is illustrated in Figure 1.
The well intersected a thin sequence of the Surat Basin comprising the Early
Jurassic Precipice Sandstone, followed by the Bowen Basin's Early Triassic
Rewan Formation sediments, and finally the Bandanna Formation. The primary
objectives for the well were the B and D coals in the Late Permian Bandanna
Formation. The B and D coals in Fairview-52 are 5.8 metres and 4.6 metres thick
respectively; the gross reservoir interval is 44.5 metres. Fairview-34 to the west
had a slightly thicker gross coal section (54.8 metres) and the B and D coals at
this location are 4.2m and 5.2m respectively. Relatively consistent coal
thicknesses development across the Field, however, indicates a low risk play.
Prognosis of this section was based on seismic line CR95A-04 and depth
conversion using regional velocity data and previous well data in the area.
However the Fairview 97 well intersected the Bandanna coals higher than
prognosed. The recently drilled Fairview's 96 and 94 to the northeast of this
location, flowed gas at rates up to 1 mmscf/d during cavitation and clean up
operations.
Fairview 97 spudded at 2230 hours, 23rd August 2005, and surface hole (311 mm)
was air drilled to 198.0 metres. Surface casing (244 mm) was set at 195.6 metres
and cemented to surface to protect the Precipice Sandstone aquifers The
production hole - intermediate section (216 mm), was air drilled to 695.0 metres.
After logging this section, the well was cased and cemented with 178 mm
production casing with the shoe set at 690.0 metres. The production - open hole
section (156 mm), then continued to be drilled to T.D. of 784.0 metres (D), 783.5
metres (L). The production - open hole section was logged, with the Bandanna
coal section then under reamed (from 156mm to 221 mm) between 692-776
metres. The well was then cavitated, cleaned and tested before being suspended
for future coal seam gas production T.D. was reached at 1530 hours, 29th August
The rig was released at 0800 hours, 16th September 2005.

2.2.1 Drilling Data Summary
Below is the operations summary for Fairview 97. It has been compiled from the tour
sheets and daily drilling reports (Appendix 1). T. Franks and D. York provided onsite
drilling supervision for Tipperary Oil and Gas (Australia) Pty Limited. Further details
are provided in the time/depth curve (Figure 2).
Surface Hole
Size: 311 mm
Interval: 17 - 198 m
Drilling Fluid: Air and Water
Fairview 97 was spudded at 22:30 hours Tuesday 23rd August 2005, using the
Mitchell Drilling Contractors Rig 150. The 311 mm hole section was drilled to 198
metres with surveys. A total of 15 joints of 245 mm 53.57 kg/m K55 surface casing
were run, set at 195.6 metres, and cemented with 46bbl at 13.5ppg lead, 31bbl at
15.6ppg tail, displaced with 47bbl, good cement returns to surface.
The BOP's were nippled up and function and pressure tested. The BOP and choke
manifold were all pressure tested to 250/1500 psi. After running in the pipe rams and
HCR, the annular were pressure tested to 250/1000 psi and shoe track was drilled out.
Production Hole - Intermediate Section
Size: 216 mm
Interval: 198 - 695 m
Drilling Fluid: Air and Water
After drilling out the shoe, the 216 mm hole was drilled to 695 metres and the hole
circulated clean. The hole was then displaced with 3% KCl-Polymer mud.
The 216 mm intermediate section was drilled to 695 metres with surveys. A wiper
trip to the shoe was run prior to pulling out of hole to run wireline logs. Wireline logs
consisted of: TLD-GR.
A total of 55 joints of 178 mm 34.22 kg/m NT 80 HE production casing being run, set
at 690 metres, and cemented with 127sx with 6%gel add lead, 150sx with 2% HR-5
add tails, displace with 90bbl.

3.0 	GEOLOGY
3.1 Reasons for Drilling
Fairview 97 is located in the Bowen Basin, within the producing coal seam gas field,
Fairview. The area straddles the Comet Ridge, between the Taroom Trough to the east
and the Denison Trough to the west. Generally, wells in this region intersect only the
basal Jurassic units of the Surat Basin, unconformably overlying the Triassic sediments
of the Bowen Basin. Within the area of the Fairview Field, the uppermost formations of
the Bowen Basin are generally absent, with the Rewan Formation intersected
immediately below the Jurassic sequence.
The well is situated between Fairview 34, Fairview 52 and Fairview 2 (1.45km south-east
of Fairview 52 and 1.8km east of Fairview-34) in PL 91, and provides data on reservoir
pressures, coal development and seismic velocity to the Bandanna Formation. The well
lies east of the Comet Ridge platform crest, west of the down-to-the-east fault that
interrupts the Bandanna section, and is spaced along the east-west 2 kilometre grid of the
current field development plan. The recently drilled Fairview's 96 and 94 to the
northeast of this location, flowed gas at rates up to 1 mmscf/d during cavitation and clean
up operations.
The primary objective for the well was coals in the Permian Bandanna Formation. The B
and D coals in Fairview 52 are 5.8 metres and 4.6 metres thick respectively; the gross
reservoir interval is 44.5 metres. Fairview-34 to the west has a slightly thicker gross coal
section (54.8 metres) and the B and D coals at this location are 4.2m and 5.2m
respectively
Relatively consistent coal thicknesses across the field indicated a low risk play.
Prognosis of this section was based on seismic line CR95A-04 and depth conversion
using regional velocity data and previous well data in the area. However the Fairview 97
well intersected the Bandanna coals higher than prognosed (Table 5).
3.2 Reservoir
The Bandanna coal, forming the Comet Ridge coal seam gas play, was the primary target
in Fairview 97. However, detailed description of the coals is not possible as no samples
were collected from this well. The target seams, Bandanna B and D, were 4.50m and
5.36m thick respectively, as picked from the wireline logs. Small gas flares were recorded
in 	the Daily Drilling Reports on connections whilst under reaming (flares 5-6 metres for up
to 10 seconds), when unloading the well during the flush. Gas flares up to 4 metres were
commonly recorded for up to 2 minutes when unloading the well during the cavitation,
cleaning and gas flow testing process. Gas rates reached a maximum of 54 Mcf/day.
